ob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705183,"age":16,"year":"1086","julianDay":2117714,"title":"Domesday Book","description":"Domesday Book is Britain's earliest extant public record with information containing land surveys and landholdings commissioned by William I. The book was completed in 1086.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/domesday/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Domesday","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705184,"age":26,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705185,"age":36,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Robert d'Avranches was born in 1070, in Okehampton, Devon, England as the son of Guillame Fitz Guimonde d'Avranches and Mathilda de Meules. He had at least 1 daughter with Adeliza de Dol. He died in 1130, in his hometown, at the age of 60."},"et":{"1070–1130":"1070–1130","1070–Male":"1070–Surnud","1079–1132":"1079–1132","1079–1153":"1079–1153","1073–Female":"1073–Surnud","1100–1175":"1100–1175","1037–1087":"1037–1087","–1142":"–1142","1132":"1132","1087":"1087","1142":"1142","1175":"1175","1153":"1153","1130":"1130","1086":"1086","1096":"1096","1073":"1073","1070":"1070","1106":"1106","1037":"1037","1079":"1079","1100":"1100","about 1100":"umbes 1100","Malpas, Cheshire, England":"Malpas, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Okehampton, Devonshire, 